# Environment Variables Template
#
# HOW THIS WORKS:
# 1. Copy this file to .env: cp .env.example .env
# 2. Update the values in .env with your actual credentials
# 3. The spring-dotenv dependency automatically loads these variables at startup
# 4. Spring can reference them in application.yaml using ${VARIABLE_NAME} syntax
#
# Example:
#   .env file:           JWT_SECRET=my-secret-key
#   application.yaml:    jwt.secret: ${JWT_SECRET}
#   Result:              Spring sets jwt.secret to "my-secret-key"
#
# IMPORTANT:
# - Never commit .env to version control (it contains secrets)
# - .env is already in .gitignore
# - .env.example is committed as a template for other developers

# ============================================
# JWT Configuration
# ============================================
# TODO: Generate a secure random secret key (at least 256 bits / 32 characters)
# You can generate one using: openssl rand -base64 32
JWT_SECRET=your-secret-key-here-change-this-in-production

